'''Nicolas Pépé''' (born 29 May 1995) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[right winger]] or [[forward (association football)|forward]] for {{Spanish football updater|Villarreal}} club [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]].

Pépé began his senior club career with [[Poitiers FC|Poitiers]] in the [[Championnat de France Amateur 2]]. He signed for [[Angers SCO|Angers]] in 2013, aged 18, and spent a season on loan at [[US Orléans|Orléans]] in 2015. He signed for [[Lille OSC|Lille]] in 2017, and was named to the [[National Union of Professional Footballers|UNFP]] Ligue 1 [[Trophées UNFP du football#Team of the Year|Team of the Year]] in the [[2018–19 Ligue 1|2018–19]] season. That summer, Pépé joined Arsenal for a then club-record fee of £72&nbsp;million, and won the [[2020 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]] in his debut season. In 2022, he was loaned to [[OGC Nice|Nice]], and then left on a free transfer to [[Trabzonspor]].

Pépé, who was born in France to Ivorian parents, made his debut for the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]] in 2016. He was selected for the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]], [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]], [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|2021]], and [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]], winning the 2023 tournament.

== Early life ==
Pépé was born in [[Mantes-la-Jolie]], Île-de-France, and grew up in the [[19th arrondissement of Paris]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nicolas Pépé |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur54623.html |access-date=29 December 2020 |newspaper=L'Équipe |location=Paris |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-02-10 |title=Nicolas Pépé, la nouvelle star de la Ligue 1|trans-title=Nicolas Pépé, the new star of Ligue 1 |url=https://www.leparisien.fr/sports/football/guingamp-lille-nicolas-pepe-la-nouvelle-star-de-la-ligue-1-10-02-2019-8008365.php |access-date=2024-01-08 |website=leparisien.fr |language=fr}}</ref> He started his career originally playing as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for local side Solitaire Paris Est until he was 14 years old.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lille's Nicolas Pepe credits goalkeeping experience for goalscoring form |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/lilles-nicolas-pepe-credits-goalkeeping-experience-for/10jg1642dtmco1f7d12jkg0rbm |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=Goal}}</ref> When his father Celestin, a prison guard, was transferred to [[Poitiers]], Pépé began his senior career as an outfield player with [[Poitiers FC]] in the [[Championnat de France Amateur 2]] (fifth tier) in 2012–13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Holyman |first1=Ian |title=Nicolas Pepe to Arsenal: Who is the £72m Gunners signing and how will he fit in? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49144687 |access-date=2 September 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=1 August 2019}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Angers===
Pépé signed for [[Angers SCO|Angers]] in 2013, and spent his first season with the reserves in the CFA 2.

He made his professional debut in the second round of the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] in a 2–1 home loss to [[AC Arles-Avignon|Arles-Avignon]] on 26 August 2014, as a 73rd-minute substitute for [[Yohann Eudeline]]. His first [[Ligue 2]] match was on 21 November 2014, starting in a 1–1 [[Ligue 2]] draw away to [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuille_match/79300|title=AC Ajaccio vs. Angers SCO|publisher=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]]|language=fr|date=21 November 2014|access-date=20 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/nicolas-pepe-le-juvenile-atout-offensif-du-sco-3004548|title=Nicolas Pépé, le juvénile atout offensif du Sco|trans-title=Nicolas Pépé, SCO's young attacking asset|work=[[Ouest-France]]|language=fr|date=24 November 2014|access-date=20 June 2015}}</ref>

====Orléans (loan)====
Pépé was [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] to [[US Orléans|Orléans]] for the [[2015–16 Championnat National]], and helped the club to promotion from the third tier as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |title=FOOTBALL L'ancien Poitevin Nicolas Pépé monte en Ligue 2 avec Orléans |trans-title=FOOTBALL Former Poitiers player Nicolas Pépé promoted to Ligue 2 with Orléans|url=https://www.centre-presse.fr/article-462606-football-l-ancien-poitevin-nicolas-pepe-monte-en-ligue-avec-orleans.html |access-date=30 January 2019 |work=Centre-Presse |date=5 June 2016 |language=fr}}</ref> He returned to an Angers side playing in [[Ligue 1]] and which reached the [[2017 Coupe de France Final]], where he started in a 1–0 loss to [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Angers 0–1 Paris Saint Germain |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39909497 |access-date=30 January 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2017}}</ref>

===Lille===
On 21 June 2017, Pépé signed a five-year deal with [[Lille OSC|Lille]], for a maximum transfer fee of €10&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Nicolas-pepe-signe-au-losc-pour-cinq-ans-off/812377|title=Nicolas Pépé et Hervé Koffi signent au Losc pour cinq ans (off.)|trans-title=Nicolas Pépé and Hervé Koffi sign for LOSO for five years (official)|work=[[L'Équipe]]|language=fr|date=21 June 2017|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref> after being signed by head coach [[Marcelo Bielsa]] who had scouted the player by watching footage of every Ligue 1 game he had played in for [[Angers SCO|Angers]], before scouting him in person.<ref name="auto1">{{cite news |title=Love at First Sight: How Nicolas Pepe Sent Europe's Top Clubs Weak at the Knees |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2831912-love-at-first-sight-how-nicolas-pepe-sent-europes-top-clubs-weak-at-the-knees |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bairner |first1=Robin |title=The French Connection: Nicolas Pepe – Europe's most wanted |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/the-french-connection-nicolas-pepe-europes-most-wanted/ry3s0n6kd77g141jfkcp20bgs |access-date=9 March 2019 |publisher=Goal |date=29 October 2019}}</ref> Pépé described Bielsa as "special" and a "great coach".<ref>{{cite news |title=LOSC: The confidences of Nicolas Pepe on Marcelo Bielsa |url=https://le10sport.com/football/ligue1/losc/losc-les-confidences-de-nicolas-pepe-sur-marcelo-bielsa-413363 |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=10 Sport}}</ref> He started the season playing as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] after being converted into playing the position under Bielsa, before finishing the season under the new [[Lille OSC|Lille]] head coach [[Christophe Galtier]], playing as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]].<ref name="auto">{{cite news |title=Nicolas Pepe: All you need to know about Lille star linked with Arsenal |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11769486/nicolas-pepe-all-you-need-to-know-about-lille-star-linked-with-manchester-united |access-date=27 July 2019 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>

During the entirety of the [[2017–18 Ligue 1]] season, he was a regular in a Lille side that narrowly avoided relegation, missing only two games and scoring 13 times, including two apiece in away wins at [[FC Metz|Metz]] and [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Adam |last2=Devin |first2=Eric |title=Lille have pulled off a miraculous escape from relegation – or have they? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/14/lille-relegation-ligue-1-monaco-psg-strasbourg-lyon |access-date=30 January 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=14 May 2018}}</ref>

On 15 September 2018, during the [[2018–19 Ligue 1]] season, Pépé scored a [[hat-trick]], including two penalties, in the 3–2 away win over [[Amiens SC|Amiens]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/pepe-hat-trick-lifts-lille-into-second.htm|title=Pepe hat-trick lifts Lille into second|publisher=Ligue 1|date=15 September 2018|access-date=18 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918193956/https://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/pepe-hat-trick-lifts-lille-into-second.htm|archive-date=18 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Days later, it was confirmed by club president [[Gérard Lopez (businessman)|Gérard Lopez]] that [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] were among several clubs that were interested in signing him.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |last=Marsden |first=Sam |date=22 September 2018 |title=Barcelona interest in Nicolas Pepe confirmed by Lille president |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37561962/barcelona-interest-nicolas-pepe-confirmed-lille-president |access-date=30 January 2019 |website=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On 14 April 2019, Pépé scored a goal and provided two [[Assist (football)|assists]] in the 5–1 home win over [[Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/brilliant-lille-blow-away-psg.htm|title=Brilliant Lille blow away PSG|publisher=Ligue 1|date=14 April 2019|access-date=15 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415062727/https://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/brilliant-lille-blow-away-psg.htm|archive-date=15 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He finished the [[2018–19 Ligue 1]] season with 22 goals, second only to PSG's [[Kylian Mbappé]],<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last1=Dunn |first1=Connor |title=The amazing statistics that prove Nicolas Pepe could've been perfect transfer for Jurgen Klopp and Liverpool |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/amazing-statistics-prove-nicolas-pepe-16448598 |access-date=6 July 2019 |work=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=19 June 2019}}</ref> with 11 assists, and was named in the [[National Union of Professional Footballers|UNFP]] [[Trophées UNFP du football#Team of the Year|Team of the Year]] and as the Lille Best Player of the season winning the Dogue de la saison award.<ref name=unfp/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sarl |first=Nas |date=15 May 2019 |title=Lille : Sans surprise, Nicolas Pépé est élu meilleur joueur de la saison |url=https://mondialsport.ci/lille-sans-surprise-nicolas-pepe-est-elu-meilleur-joueur-de-la-saison-6235.sport |access-date=14 February 2024 |website=Mondialsport.ci |language=fr}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite web |date=2 August 2019 |title=Expert view on Nicolas Pepe – The best player in France behind Mbappe who was shaped by Bielsa |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/transfers-3/2018-2019/expert-view-on-nicolas-pepe-the-best-player-in-france-behind-mbappe-who-was-shaped-by-bielsa_sto7394249/story.shtml |access-date=14 February 2024 |website=Euro Sport}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
On 1 August 2019, it was announced that Pépé had joined [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in a then club-record fee of €80&nbsp;million (£72&nbsp;million),<ref>{{cite news |date=1 August 2019 |title=Arsenal confirm signing of Nicolas Pépé from Lille in £72m club-record deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/01/arsenal-sign-nicolas-pepe-lille-record-deal |access-date=16 April 2025 |work=[[The Guardian]] |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> eclipsing the previous record of €62&nbsp;million for [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]]. Upon signing for Arsenal, he was handed the number 19 shirt.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/nicolas-pepe-becomes-record-signing|title=#PepeIsHere {{!}} Nicolas Pepe becomes record signing |access-date=1 August 2019 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref>

Pépé made his Arsenal debut in a 1–0 away win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 11 August, as a substitute for [[Reiss Nelson]] in the 71st minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49223797 |title=Newcastle United 0–1 Arsenal |publisher=BBC |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=11 August 2019 |access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> His first start for the club came two weeks later in a 3–1 loss to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], in which he played the full 90 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49378898|title=Liverpool 3–1 Arsenal|publisher=BBC|date=24 August 2019|access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref> He scored his first Arsenal goal, from the penalty spot, in the team's 3–2 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 22 September.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ames |first1=Nick |title=Aubameyang breaks Aston Villa hearts as 10-man Arsenal bounce back late on |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/sep/22/arsenal-aston-villa-premier-league-match-report |access-date=1 July 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=22 September 2019}}</ref> He scored his first European goals in Arsenal's [[UEFA Europa League]] 3–2 home win over [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória de Guimarães]] on 24 October, two free-kicks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50159121|title=Arsenal 3-2 Vitoria Guimaraes: Nicolas Pepe rescues Gunners in Europe|date=24 October 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 1 January 2020, Pépé scored Arsenal's first goal in a 2–0 home victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], marking new head-coach [[Mikel Arteta]]'s first win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50908732|title=Arsenal 2-0 Man Utd: Gunners secure first win under Mikel Arteta|date=1 January 2020|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 16 February, Pépé scored once and assisted twice in a 4–0 win over Newcastle United. On 28 June, he scored his first [[FA Cup]] goal in a 2–1 away win against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in the quarter-finals, giving Arsenal the lead in the 25th minute from the penalty spot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53139211|title=Sheffield United 1–2 Arsenal: Dani Ceballos' late goal sends Arsenal to FA Cup semis|date=28 June 2020|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 1 August, he played the whole 90 minutes of the [[2020 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] match against Chelsea to win his first club trophy as an Arsenal player, contributing the assist for Aubameyang's second goal.<ref>{{Cite news|date=1 August 2020|title=FA Cup final 2020: Arsenal 2-1 Chelsea - Aubameyang double secures victory|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53546100|access-date=1 August 2020}}</ref>

Pépé received the first red card of his career on 22 November 2020 in a 0–0 away draw against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] after clashing heads with [[Ezgjan Alioski]] in the 51st minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54948353 |title=Leeds United 0–0 Arsenal: Nicolas Pepe sent off in goalless draw |last=Begley |first=Emlyn |date=22 November 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 2 February 2021, he beat two defenders before scoring in a game against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]; that goal was later voted as Goal of the Month for February on Arsenal's official website.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Wolves beat nine-man Arsenal at Molineux |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55806209 |access-date=10 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pepe tops our February Goal of the Month poll |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/pepe-tops-our-february-goal-month-poll |access-date=10 March 2021 |website=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref>

On 24 February 2022, Pépé scored his first goal of the [[2021–22 Premier League]] season in a 2–1 win against Wolverhampton with an 82nd-minute strike, and was instrumental in the buildup of forcing an own goal in the 95th minute to cap a late comeback.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal vs. Wolverhampton Wanderers - Football Match Summary |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/605848 |date=24 February 2022 |website=ESPN |access-date=25 February 2022}}</ref>

Pépé played 112 games over all competitions for Arsenal, scoring 27 goals. He took no part in the start of the [[2022–23 Arsenal F.C. season|2022–23 season]] in his last month at the club.<ref name=nice/> On 25 August 2022, he joined Ligue 1 club [[OGC Nice|Nice]] on loan for the remainder of the [[2022–23 OGC Nice season|2022–23 season]] without an option to buy.<ref name= nice>{{cite news |title=Nicolas Pepe: Nice sign Arsenal and Ivory Coast winger on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62681815 |access-date=6 September 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2025}}</ref>

===Trabzonspor===
Pépé moved to [[Süper Lig]] side [[Trabzonspor]] on 8 September 2023.<ref name="trabzonspor">{{cite news |title=Nicolas Pepe: Arsenal winger joins Trabzonspor |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66747448 |access-date=8 September 2023 |work=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2023}}</ref> He departed Arsenal on a free transfer, having had one year left on his contract.<ref name="trabzonspor"/>

===Villarreal===
On 4 August 2024, Pépé signed for [[La Liga]] club [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] on a free transfer. He signed a two-year deal, and joined compatriot [[Eric Bailly]].<ref>{{cite news |date=4 August 2024 |title=Transfers Nicolas Pepe completes Villarreal move as free agent |url=https://en.africatopsports.com/2024/08/04/nicolas-pepe-completes-villarreal-move-as-free-agent/ |access-date=6 September 2025 |publisher=Africa Top Sports}}</ref> In his first season with the club, he made 28 appearances and contributed to 9 goals, scoring 3 times and providing 6 assists.

In July 2025, he signed a new deal to last until 2028.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sossou |first1=Joshua |title=Official: Nicolas Pépé extends his stay with Villarreal |url=https://foot-africa.com/en/news/official-nicolas-pepe-extends-his-stay-with-villarreal-800150/ |access-date=6 September 2025 |publisher=Foot Africa |date=16 July 2025}}</ref> He began the 2025–26 season in excellent form, earning the [[La Liga Player of the Month]] award for August after standout performances that included two goals and an assist in Villarreal's opening three matches.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-09-12 |title=🌟A flying start: Nicolas Pépé named La Liga player of the month |url=https://onefootball.com/es/noticias/a-flying-start-nicolas-pepe-named-la-liga-player-of-the-month-41653048 |access-date=2025-09-15 |website=OneFootball |language=es}}</ref>

==International career==
Pépé was born in France to Ivorian parents.<ref>{{cite news |date=16 October 2018 |title=Ivorian Nicolas Pepe succeeds Kylian Mbappe as player of the month |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45878964 |access-date=16 April 2025 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> He received a call up to the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]] in November 2016, and was an unused substitute in the goalless draw away to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]] on 12 November.<ref>{{cite web |title=Morocco 0–0 Côte d'Ivoire |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276412/match=300367122/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819034625/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276412/match=300367122/index.html |archive-date=19 August 2016 |access-date=6 April 2018 |publisher=FIFA}}</ref> He made his debut three days later in a friendly of the same score against his birth nation, [[France national football team|France]], at the [[Stade Bollaert-Delelis]] in [[Lens, France|Lens]], playing the final four minutes in place of [[Max-Alain Gradel]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/friendlies/season=2018/matches/round=2000741/match=2020781/postmatch/commentary/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226083804/http://www.uefa.com/friendlies/season=2018/matches/round=2000741/match=2020781/postmatch/commentary/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 December 2016|title=Friendlies 2014–16 – France-Ivory Coast |publisher=UEFA|access-date=6 April 2018}}</ref>

[[File:Joueur guinéen et ivoirien 03.jpg|thumb|right|Pépé in action with Ivory Coast during the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]]]]

Pépé was named in [[Michel Dussuyer]]'s 23-man squad for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Gabon, but took no part as the Elephants were eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Afcon 2017: Wilfried Zaha in Ivory Coast's final squad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38451141 |access-date=30 January 2019 |work=BBC Sport |date=4 January 2017}}</ref>

On 24 March 2018, in a friendly against [[Togo national football team|Togo]] in France, Pépé scored his first international goals in the first half of a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{cite news |title=Togo/Cote d'Ivoire: Amical – La difficile semaine des eléphants|trans-title=Togo/Ivory Coast: Friendly – The Elephants' difficult week |url=https://fr.allafrica.com/stories/201803260607.html |access-date=30 January 2019 |publisher=All Africa |date=26 March 2018 |language=fr}}</ref> He followed it three days later, with another goal in a 2–1 win against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] in the same stadium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amical – La Côte d'Ivoire l'a emporté sur la Moldavie|trans-title=Friendly – The Ivory Coast swept past Moldova |url=http://www.madeinfoot.com/infos/article-amical-la-cote-d-ivoire-l-a-emporte-sur-la-moldavie-226592.html |access-date=30 January 2019 |publisher=Made in Foot |date=28 March 2018 |language=fr}}</ref>

Pépé was called up for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Egypt.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barrie |first1=Mohamed Fajah |title=Africa Cup of Nations: Bony named in Ivory Coast's final squad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48574328 |access-date=2 June 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 June 2019}}</ref> He was absent from their quarter-final penalty shootout defeat by [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]], having been dropped for [[Max Alain Gradel]] due to a lack of form.<ref>{{cite news |title=Algeria edge Ivory Coast on penalties to make Africa Cup of Nations semis |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190711-algeria-ivory-coast-football-africa-cup-nations-sport-semis |access-date=2 June 2021 |publisher=France 24 |date=11 July 2019}}</ref>

At the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Cameroon, Pépé scored in a draw with [[Sierra Leone national football team|Sierra Leone]] and a win over holders Algeria in the group stage.<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Roché |first1=Art |title=Sharper in possession and making more impact with fewer touches: Arsenal need the AFCON version of Nicolas Pepe |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3093386/2022/01/26/sharper-in-possession-and-making-more-impact-with-fewer-touches-arsenal-need-the-afcon-version-of-nicolas-pepe/ |access-date=6 September 2025 |work=The Athletic |date=27 January 2022}}</ref>

Pépé missed over a year of international football between November 2022 and being chosen for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sannie |first1=Ibrahim |title=AFCON 2023: Cote d'Ivoire names final squad without Wilfried Zaha, Pepe returns |url=https://africasoccer.com/afcon-2023-tournament-hosts-cote-divoire-names-final-squad-without-wilfried-zaha-while-nicolas-pepe-returns/ |access-date=6 September 2025 |publisher=Africa Soccer |date=28 December 2023}}</ref> At the tournament on home soil, he won a late penalty that [[Franck Kessié]] converted to take the game to extra time and a penalty shootout victory over reigning champions Senegal,<ref>{{cite news |title=AFCON 2023: Ivory Coast knock out holders Senegal after 5-4 penalty shootout win |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13059608/afcon-2023-ryan-mendes-88th-minute-penalty-sees-cape-verde-past-mauritania-and-into-quarter-finals |access-date=6 September 2025 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=30 January 2024}}</ref> en route to winning the title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Anka |first1=Carl |last2=Whitehead |first2=Jacob |title=AFCON final: Haller's fairytale finish seals glory as Nigeria and Osimhen fall short |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5267230/2024/02/11/afcon-final-ivory-coast-haller-osimhen-nigeria/ |access-date=6 September 2025 |work=The Athletic |date=11 February 2024}}</ref>

On May 15, 2026, Pépé was integrated by Ivory Coast coach [[Emerse Faé]] in his list of 26 players in order to participate in the [[2026 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=2 June 2026 |date=15 May 2026 |language=fr |title=La liste de la Côte d'Ivoire pour la Coupe du Monde 2026 |url=https://www.fifa.com/fr/articles/liste-cote-d-ivoire-coupe-du-monde-2026 |website=[[FIFA]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

==Style of play==
Pépé is known as a quick and skilled attacking [[Winger (association football)|winger]] who is comfortable on both flanks, but usually plays on the [[Winger (association football)|right wing]] cutting onto his left foot; he was also converted from playing in wide positions by former Lille head coach [[Marcelo Bielsa]] to play as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] on either the inside or central channel.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Scout Reports: Nicolas Pépé: Premier League Player Watch |url=https://www.coachesvoice.com/cv/nicolas-pepe-arsenal-mikel-arteta/ |website=Coaches' Voice |publisher=Wyscout |access-date=20 May 2022}}</ref>

==Media==
Pépé was involved in the [[List of Amazon Prime Video original programming|Amazon Original]] sports [[docuseries]] ''[[All or Nothing: Arsenal]]'', which documented the club by spending time with the coaching staff and players behind the scenes both on and off the field throughout their [[2021–22 Arsenal F.C. season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/full-all-or-nothing-trailer-released |title=Full 'All Or Nothing' trailer released |date=19 July 2022 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=21 July 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |date=19 July 2022 |title=All or Nothing: Arsenal {{pipe}} Official Full Trailer 🎬 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ta3CLkX-bzk |access-date=21 July 2022 |publisher=[[Amazon Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video Sport]] |via=[[YouTube]] }}</ref>

